Anonymous Wed 08 Mar 2023 17:33:07 No.54917638 Report
Quoted By: >>54917720
>>54916538
And strangely enough, I still don't understand the popularity of the older stuff despite reading through it multiple times.

I'd argue that a few factors are at play here
1 - the burnout factor; so many people are used to being disappointed at stories that they won't touch unfinished ones, even if they update on a schedule
2 - time factor; take haapy as a recent example. Finished story at about 140k words, but he's unlikely to see a readership bump
3 - nostalgia vs primacy; so combining the above two, you're far more likely to get a positive word about something older (like alfa's stuff, which does deserve its reputation) than chapter 3 of $recent_story, even if both have the exact same quality or issues
4 - passion projects; I'll slag on haapy again. No matter how good he gets as a writer, a writefag will get attention if their stuff has a base beyond them. If you don't, you've struck out and have to keep going without that feel-good boost of (you) coming back. Some people can deal with that (haapy) and others dwindle off.

Maybe I should be the change I want to see and do a readying of older & longer stories that are completed but no one else but me remembers.
So thank for pushing me to the idea.

Anonymous Wed 08 Mar 2023 18:26:32 No.54918556 Report
Quoted By: >>54918891
>>54918197
>And he and the editor need to sit down and make an outline of the story
That's the key.

If you don't outline, if you just write off of the cuff, you need to be your own editor and have an innate sense of what's going to be cohesive (or at least coherent) down the road. If you don't have that sense, it's very easy to create an endless serial that goes nowhere. That's a fine career for soap opera writers, but in written form you have an issue of the accumulating material. Nobody watches a soap opera from the first episode unless one is there when the first episode airs. But a story sends everyone to page 1 and 200k words of stuff is a lot to slog through if the author never had an idea of what his fucking point was the whole way.
